{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Per-creator index / global swapId confusion lets callers withdraw other users' escrowed assets","locations":["0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:161","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:197","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:222","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:273","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:280"],"claim":"`swapMatch[swapId]` stores only the swap creator's local array index, but `closeSwapIntent` and `cancelSwapIntent` combine that local index with caller-supplied creator addresses while always moving assets from the global `nftsOne[_swapId]` / `nftsTwo[_swapId]` buckets. A user who has an opened swap at the same local index as a victim can satisfy the ownership/status checks against their own swap entry and operate on the victim swap's escrowed assets.","impact":"Attackers can steal NFTs, ERC20s, ERC1155s, or CryptoPunks escrowed in another user's `nftsOne` bucket. The victim's actual swap record is left open or otherwise inconsistent, which can strand any ETH tracked in the victim's swap struct and make recovery impossible.","paths":["Victim creates swap `V` at local index `i`, so `swapMatch[V] = i` and `nftsOne[V]` holds the victim's escrowed assets.","Attacker creates any opened swap at their own local index `i`.","Attacker calls `cancelSwapIntent(V)`.","The function validates `swapList[attacker][i]`, but transfers `nftsOne[V]` back to the attacker and marks the attacker's own swap entry cancelled."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"User-controlled `typeStd` can route whitelisted assets through an unset custom bridge and bypass escrow entirely","locations":["0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:172","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:187","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:223","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:238","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:335"],"claim":"The contract whitelists only `dapp` addresses and trusts the caller-supplied `typeStd`. Any `typeStd` value other than the three hardcoded sentinels or `CRYPTOPUNK` falls into the custom-bridge branch, which blindly calls `dappRelations[dapp]` without checking that a relation is configured or that it is a real bridge contract. For an ordinary whitelisted token with no bridge relation, these calls can succeed while moving no assets.","impact":"A maker or taker can advertise escrow that was never deposited, then receive the counterparty's real NFTs/ERC20s/ETH while their own side transfers nothing.","paths":["A standard token/collection is whitelisted, but `dappRelations[dapp]` is unset or points to a non-bridge address.","Attacker creates a swap using that whitelisted `dapp` but supplies an arbitrary nonstandard `typeStd`, forcing the custom bridge path.","`createSwapIntent` records the swap even though the attacker's asset transfer is a no-op.","A victim closes the swap; their side transfers normally, while the attacker's side again uses the no-op bridge path and delivers nothing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"ERC20 transfers are treated as successful even when the token signals failure","locations":["0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:13","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:174","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:225","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:249","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:282"],"claim":"The custom ERC20 interface omits the standard boolean return values, and every ERC20 `transfer` / `transferFrom` call ignores success. Tokens that fail by returning `false` instead of reverting therefore appear to the contract as successful deposits, payouts, or refunds.","impact":"A maker can create a swap whose ERC20 escrow was never actually deposited, or a taker can receive the maker's escrowed assets without paying the requested ERC20 consideration. Failed ERC20 refunds during cancellation can likewise leave users with a cancelled swap but no returned tokens.","paths":["Victim creates a swap that requires a whitelisted ERC20 in `nftsTwo`, or relies on an ERC20 in `nftsOne` being escrowed.","Attacker closes the swap without a real balance/allowance, using a token that returns `false` on failure.","The `transferFrom` call at line 249 returns `false`, but `BatchSwap` continues executing.","The victim's escrowed assets and ETH transfer anyway, even though the ERC20 payment never occurred."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"`cancelSwapIntent` is reentrant through token or bridge callbacks before the swap is marked cancelled","locations":["0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:273","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:277","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:281","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:295","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:300","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:303"],"claim":"`cancelSwapIntent` performs external token and bridge calls, and refunds ETH, before it sets `swapEnd` and `status = Cancelled`. If the swap creator is a contract and one of its whitelisted assets or bridge endpoints reenters during the loop, nested `cancelSwapIntent` calls will still see the swap as `Opened` and can withdraw `swapFee` and `valueOne` repeatedly from the contract's shared ETH balance.","impact":"A malicious swap creator can drain ETH that belongs to other users' swaps, leaving the contract insolvent and causing unrelated settlements or cancellations to fail.","paths":["Attacker creates a swap from a contract address and includes a malicious whitelisted token or bridge-controlled asset in `nftsOne`.","Attacker calls `cancelSwapIntent` through that contract.","During the external transfer at lines 281-296, the malicious token/bridge reenters `cancelSwapIntent` for the same swap before line 303 executes.","Each nested call refunds `swapFee` and `valueOne` again, draining pooled ETH from the contract."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Using Solidity `transfer` for ETH payouts can permanently brick swaps involving contract recipients","locations":["0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:205","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:210","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:243","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:267","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:278","0xc310e760778ecbca4c65b6c559874757a4c4ece0/contracts/BatchSwap.sol:301"],"claim":"All ETH payouts use Solidity's `transfer`, which hardcodes a 2300-gas stipend and reverts if the recipient is a contract with a nontrivial or intentionally reverting receive/fallback path. This affects fee forwarding, settlement payouts, and cancellation refunds.","impact":"Swaps that involve contract wallets, proxies, vaults, or other recipients that cannot accept a 2300-gas `transfer` can become uncloseable or uncancellable, permanently locking escrowed NFTs and ETH until the affected address is changed, if that is even possible.","paths":["A swap creator, counterparty, or configured fee vault is a contract whose receive/fallback path reverts or needs more than 2300 gas.","`closeSwapIntent` or `cancelSwapIntent` reaches one of the `transfer` calls.","The ETH transfer reverts, which reverts the entire close/cancel attempt.","Escrowed assets remain locked in `BatchSwap`, and some address combinations cannot be repaired on-chain."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Reentrancy Vulnerability in ETH Transfers","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`closeSwapIntent` sets the swap status to `Closed` before any ETH payout, and Solidity `transfer` forwards only 2300 gas, so the claimed fallback-based reentrancy path is not viable."},{"title":"Owner Can Steal All Assets via Address Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an owner-trust/governance concern, not an unintended protocol bug. Changing `VAULT` redirects future fees, not existing user escrow, and malicious owner address changes are outside the normal threat model."},{"title":"Swap Creator Can Edit Counterpart After Asset Deposit","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"There is no prior counterparty deposit to steal. `nftsTwo` and `valueTwo` are pulled atomically from the caller during `closeSwapIntent`, so changing `addressTwo` does not confiscate already-escrowed assets from someone else."},{"title":"PunkProxy Reinitialization Vulnerability","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This describes user key-management / recovery limitations, not an exploitable protocol flaw."},{"title":"Owner Can Pause and Set Malicious Payment Configuration","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is another owner-trust concern rather than an unintended permissionless exploit."},{"title":"Missing Expiration Check for Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`swapEnd` is used as a completion timestamp, not an expiry promise. Counterparty assets are not pre-deposited, so the described permanent lockup path is not supported by the code."},{"title":"No Slippage Protection for NFT Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is inherent market risk in fixed-term OTC swaps, not a smart-contract vulnerability."},{"title":"Missing check for contract existence before external calls","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"As written this mostly relies on admin miswhitelisting. The materially reportable user-triggerable version is the `typeStd` custom-bridge bypass captured in F-002."},{"title":"Inconsistent Access Control on WhiteList Management","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The claim is factually incorrect: `setWhitelist(address,bool)` can both add and remove whitelist entries by setting the boolean status."},{"title":"Missing Event Emission for Critical State Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Lack of events is a transparency issue, not a realistic protocol-level asset loss or lockup vulnerability."},{"title":"Incorrect ERC20 Interface Definition","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The parameter name `tokenId` is irrelevant to the ABI; the function selector matches `transferFrom(address,address,uint256)`."},{"title":"Missing Contract Balance Recovery Function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Accidental direct transfers to the contract are a usability issue, not an exploitable protocol vulnerability in the swap flow."}]}
